THE SHINING

 

THE

SHINING

 

The Shining

The Shining is a horror film produced and directed by Stanley Kubrick and co-written with novelist Diane Johnson. The film is based on Stephen King's 1977 novel of the same name.

 

Because of inconsistencies, ambiguities, symbolism, and differences from the book, there has been much speculation into the meanings and action in the movie.

There were several versions for theatrical releases, each shorter than the prior, with about 27 minutes cut. Although contemporary responses from critics were mixed, assessment became more favorable in the following decades, and it is now widely regarded as one of the greatest horror films ever made. The Shining is acclaimed by today's critics and has become a staple of pop culture.

Shelley Duvall, Stanley Kubrick and Jack Nicholson The Shining

 

 

 

 

Jack Nicholson reflected on the Duvall/Kubrick relationship in a documentary titled Stanley Kubrick: A Life in Pictures. He drew attention to the double standards with which the director approached him and his co-star. Kubrick was on the same page with Nicholson and treated him with respect but was always critical of Duvall. This was part of Kubrick’s plan, it seems.

 

 

As Vivian Kubrick confirmed in the commentary in The Making of The Shining, Stanley Kubrick deliberately bullied Duvall to enhance the insecurity of Wendy Torrance.

He could even be heard in the film saying to the other crew members while she was standing right next to him, "Don’t sympathize with Shelley".

 

In the book, the spooky events are set in Room 217, not Room 237. Oregon's Timberline Lodge, which was used as the hotel’s exterior for some shots, is to blame for this swap. The Lodge’s management asked for the room number to be changed so that guests wouldn’t avoid Room 217. There is no Room 237 in the hotel, so that number was chosen. The website of The Timberline Lodge notes, "Curiously and somewhat ironically, room #217 is requested more often than any other room at Timberline."

Garrett Brown and his invention

 

 

 

 

Garrett Brown carries Danny Lloyd on steadicam

 

 

 

 

"

 

He’s not like a film director, (rather a) medieval artisan working in an ivory tower, sculpting until he had perfect image.

 

— Garrett Brown, the Steadicam Operator

The film contains two mazes, the hedges outside, and for Wendy's characterization, the Overlook itself. The hedge maze appears in two forms, the 13-foot-high version outside, and the model inside the Overlook. In addition, in the overhead shot zooming down on Wendy and Danny in the center of the maze, the maze differs from the map outside and from the model not only in having far more corridors but also in the fact that the left and right sides are mirror images of each other.

 

 

Stanley Kubrick in the snow labyrinth

 

900 tons of salt and expanded polystyrene were used to construct the scenery of the snow maze at the end of the film. The maze itself was built full size at the airfield near the "Elstree Studios," and it was easy to really get lost in it.

 

 

the shining of Steadicam

 

 

 

The film was one of the first in the filming of which Steadicam camera stabilization system was used. Some scenes in which the camera moves (Danny drives through the corridors on a bicycle, Danny and Wendy walk through the maze, Danny runs away from Jack) were filmed using this device. The inventor of the system Garrett Brown took a full part in the shooting as one of the operators; an article about him was published in the journal American Cinematographer. Almost all shots from Danny were taken "from the hip"—that is, at the level of the child’s eyes. Kubrick did that to show the environment from Danny's point of view. For the filming of these scenes, Garrett Brown fixed the camera not at the top, but at the bottom of the Steadicam system, specially designed for shooting from the bottom.

 

At the same time, the counter weight with the monitor was fixed on the top platform. Due to that, he was able to walk freely while shooting, straightening to his full height, and the camera was located at the level of his knees. In between filming, Brown took a camera from the floor and put Danny Lloyd in there, because the boy weighed almost as much as the machine.
